3.1. Probabilistic Rand Index
Consider a set of manually segmented (ground truth) images {S1 , S2 , . . . , SK } corresponding to an image X = {x1 , x2 , . . . xi , . . . , xN }, where a subscript indexes one of N pixels. Let Stest be the segmentation that is to be compared with the manually labeled set. We denote the label of S S point xi by li test in segmentation Stest and by li k in the manS ually segmented image Sk . It is assumed that each label li k can take values in a discrete set of size Lk , and correspondS ingly li test takes one of Ltest values. We chose to model label relationships for each pixel pair by an unknown underlying distribution. One may visualize this as a scenario where each human segmenter provides information about the segmentation Sk of the image in the

Then the PR index can be written as: PR(Stest , {Sk }) = 1
